Wei and Zhang hope these robots can help people in the future. For example, doctors could use them inside the human body to help with surgery. Then, the robot would safely disappear inside the patient. However, the technology is still new. Scientists say that the electronic parts inside the robots are not biodegradable yet. We still need to find a way to make the whole robot disappear, not just the arm.', 'published', '2025-12-17 07:45:11.179182', '2025-12-17 07:28:28.727146');
INSERT INTO public.versions (id, article_id, level, title, content, source, syllabus_coverage, library_tags, stages, value_tags, grading_data, original_content, status, published_at, created_at) VALUES (11, 4, 'L2', 'Biodegradable Robots: A Green Future', 'When you imagine a robot, you probably think of a strong, metal machine that is more powerful than a human body. However, this durability creates a major environmental issue. Traditional robots generate a large amount of long-lasting electronic waste, or "e-waste," which creates pollution on our planet. Scientists are now asking a different question: What if machines were designed to break down and disappear, just like living plants and animals do?

In a recent study published in *Science Advances*, researchers successfully created a robotic arm and a controller using natural materials found in plants and animals. These materials are strong enough to perform mechanical tasks, but they can also break down easily in a natural environment. This type of technology is part of "soft robotics," a field that borrows ideas from nature. Florian Hartmann, a materials scientist from Germany, explains that this field began in chemistry and materials science rather than traditional mechanical engineering. While early models of soft robots still used man-made materials that caused pollution, new methods are beginning to change that.

To solve the pollution problem, Wei, a scientist in Hangzhou who studies natural materials, collaborated with Zhang, a robotics engineer in Shanghai. They started their construction process with cellulose, which is a common material taken from cotton. Then, they added glycerol to create a new substance that is soft and flexible. After allowing the material to dry, it became hard and strong. "Cellulose is cheap and easy to work with," Wei notes. During their tests, they found that the robotic arm and controller could handle heavy use. Finally, to test the biodegradability, they buried the parts in soil. Within just eight weeks, the robots had almost completely disappeared.

Wei and Zhang believe that biodegradable robots like these have a bright future. They could be used to handle dangerous waste and then vanish naturally, leaving no trash behind. The researchers also hope that such robots could help doctors during surgeries and then safely break down inside the human body. However, it is important to note that the technology is still in its early stages. Hartmann points out a significant challenge that remains. "If we truly want to have a biodegradable robot," he says, "we also need to make sure its electronics and power parts are biodegradable."', 'AI生成', '{"junior": {"coverage": 0.64, "stage_matches": {"stage1": {"stage_name": "\u7834\u51b0\u671f (Novice)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0"], "actual": "L2"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage2": {"stage_name": "\u8fdb\u9636\u671f (Intermediate)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0", "L1"], "actual": "L2"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage3": {"stage_name": "\u7a81\u7834\u671f (Advanced)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L1", "L2"], "actual": "L2"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": false}}, "match": false, "reason": "\u9898\u6750\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage4": {"stage_name": "\u51b2\u523a\u671f (Elite)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L2", "L3"], "actual": "L2"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": true}}, "match": true, "tag": "\u9ad8\u5206\u7a81\u7834", "coverage": 0.64}}}, "senior": {"coverage": 0.66, "stage_matches": {"stage1": {"stage_name": "\u7b51\u57fa\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0", "L1"], "actual": "L2"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage2": {"stage_name": "\u722c\u5761\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L1", "L2"], "actual": "L2"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": false}}, "match": false, "reason": "\u9898\u6750\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage3": {"stage_name": "\u653b\u575a\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L2"], "actual": "L2"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": false}}, "match": false, "reason": "\u9898\u6750\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage4": {"stage_name": "\u9738\u699c\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L3"], "actual": "L2"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}}}}', '["junior_stage4"]', '{"junior": [], "senior": []}', '{"junior": [], "senior": []}', '{"level": "L3", "level_name": "\u5b66\u672f\u6311\u6218 (Level 3)", "tags": {"genre": "Expository", "genre_sub": "Science", "domain": "Man & Nature", "topic_sub": "Ecology"}, "dimensions": {"vocab_profile": {"ngsl_coverage": 0.789, "nawl_ratio": 0.054, "level": "L3"}, "avg_sentence_length": {"value": 16.6, "level": "L2"}, "fkgl_score": {"value": 11.2, "level": "L3"}, "complex_sentence_density": {"value": 0.826, "count": 19, "level": "L3"}, "word_count": {"value": 382, "level": "L2"}}}', 'When you imagine a robot, you probably think of a strong, metal machine that is more powerful than a human body. However, this durability creates a major environmental issue. Traditional robots generate a large amount of long-lasting electronic waste, or "e-waste," which creates pollution on our planet. Scientists are now asking a different question: What if machines were designed to break down and disappear, just like living plants and animals do?

In a recent study published in *Science Advances*, researchers successfully created a robotic arm and a controller using natural materials found in plants and animals. These materials are strong enough to perform mechanical tasks, but they can also break down easily in a natural environment. This type of technology is part of "soft robotics," a field that borrows ideas from nature. Florian Hartmann, a materials scientist from Germany, explains that this field began in chemistry and materials science rather than traditional mechanical engineering. While early models of soft robots still used man-made materials that caused pollution, new methods are beginning to change that.

To solve the pollution problem, Wei, a scientist in Hangzhou who studies natural materials, collaborated with Zhang, a robotics engineer in Shanghai. They started their construction process with cellulose, which is a common material taken from cotton. Then, they added glycerol to create a new substance that is soft and flexible. After allowing the material to dry, it became hard and strong. "Cellulose is cheap and easy to work with," Wei notes. During their tests, they found that the robotic arm and controller could handle heavy use. Finally, to test the biodegradability, they buried the parts in soil. Within just eight weeks, the robots had almost completely disappeared.

Wei and Zhang believe that biodegradable robots like these have a bright future. They could be used to handle dangerous waste and then vanish naturally, leaving no trash behind. The researchers also hope that such robots could help doctors during surgeries and then safely break down inside the human body. However, it is important to note that the technology is still in its early stages. Hartmann points out a significant challenge that remains. "If we truly want to have a biodegradable robot," he says, "we also need to make sure its electronics and power parts are biodegradable."', 'published', '2025-12-17 07:45:11.187607', '2025-12-17 07:28:28.727147');
INSERT INTO public.versions (id, article_id, level, title, content, source, syllabus_coverage, library_tags, stages, value_tags, grading_data, original_content, status, published_at, created_at) VALUES (9, 4, 'L3', 'Biodegradable Robots: A Green Future', 'Imagine a robot. What comes to your mind first? A machine stronger than the human body? However, this same quality is now causing a big problem—it''s creating tons of long-lasting e-waste that could flood our planet. What if, instead, the machines we use were designed to break down and disappear—just as living things do?
For a study published in Science Advances, researchers made a robotic arm and a controller using materials from animals and plants. These materials are strong enough to work but can easily break down in a natural environment. After testing, both parts were gone in soil within weeks.
Biodegradable robotics often falls under the umbrella of soft robotics, which takes ideas from nature. "This field started in materials science and chemistry rather than traditional robots that come from mechanical engineering," says Florian Hartmann, a materials scientist from Germany. However, many early soft robotics models still used man-made materials that cause pollution.
Wei, a scientist who studies natural materials in Hangzhou, worked together with his friend Zhang, a robotics engineer in Shanghai, to build robots for the new study. They started with cellulose taken from cotton. Then, they added glycerol to make a new material that is soft and easy to change shapes. After that they allowed it to dry so it became strong. "Cellulose is cheap and easy to work with," says Wei. They found that the controller and the robotic arm stood up to both heavy use and a week of inactivity. Finally, they buried them both in a hole. Within eight weeks these two parts were almost completely gone.
Wei and Zhang expect that robots like these can be used to deal with dangerous waste and then disappear naturally. They also hope that such robots can aid doctors in operations and then safely break down inside the body.
However, it''s important to note that the technology is still in very early stages. "If we truly want to have a biodegradable robot," Hartmann says, "we also need to make sure its electronics and power parts are biodegradable."
 

 
 ', '考试真题', '{"junior": {"coverage": 0.67, "stage_matches": {"stage1": {"stage_name": "\u7834\u51b0\u671f (Novice)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage2": {"stage_name": "\u8fdb\u9636\u671f (Intermediate)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0", "L1"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage3": {"stage_name": "\u7a81\u7834\u671f (Advanced)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L1", "L2"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage4": {"stage_name": "\u51b2\u523a\u671f (Elite)", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L2", "L3"], "actual": "L3"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": true}}, "match": true, "tag": "\u9ad8\u5206\u7a81\u7834", "coverage": 0.67}}}, "senior": {"coverage": 0.66, "stage_matches": {"stage1": {"stage_name": "\u7b51\u57fa\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L0", "L1"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage2": {"stage_name": "\u722c\u5761\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L1", "L2"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage3": {"stage_name": "\u653b\u575a\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": false, "expected": ["L2"], "actual": "L3"}}, "match": false, "reason": "Level\u4e0d\u5339\u914d"}, "stage4": {"stage_name": "\u9738\u699c\u671f", "filters": {"level": {"passed": true, "expected": ["L3"], "actual": "L3"}, "genre": {"passed": true}, "topic": {"passed": true}}, "match": true, "tag": "\u9ad8\u5206\u7a81\u7834", "coverage": 0.66}}}}', '["senior_stage4", "junior_stage4"]', '{"junior": [], "senior": []}', '{"junior": [], "senior": []}', '{"level": "L3", "level_name": "\u5b66\u672f\u6311\u6218 (Level 3)", "tags": {"genre": "Expository", "genre_sub": "Science", "domain": "Man & Nature", "topic_sub": "Ecology"}, "dimensions": {"vocab_profile": {"ngsl_coverage": 0.757, "nawl_ratio": 0.058, "level": "L3"}, "avg_sentence_length": {"value": 15.0, "level": "L2"}, "fkgl_score": {"value": 9.3, "level": "L3"}, "complex_sentence_density": {"value": 0.696, "count": 16, "level": "L3"}, "word_count": {"value": 346, "level": "L2"}}}', 'Imagine a robot. What comes to your mind first? A machine stronger than the human body? However, this same quality is now causing a big problem—it''s creating tons of long-lasting e-waste that could flood our planet. What if, instead, the machines we use were designed to break down and disappear—just as living things do?
For a study published in Science Advances, researchers made a robotic arm and a controller using materials from animals and plants. These materials are strong enough to work but can easily break down in a natural environment. After testing, both parts were gone in soil within weeks.
Biodegradable robotics often falls under the umbrella of soft robotics, which takes ideas from nature. "This field started in materials science and chemistry rather than traditional robots that come from mechanical engineering," says Florian Hartmann, a materials scientist from Germany. However, many early soft robotics models still used man-made materials that cause pollution.
Wei, a scientist who studies natural materials in Hangzhou, worked together with his friend Zhang, a robotics engineer in Shanghai, to build robots for the new study. They started with cellulose taken from cotton. Then, they added glycerol to make a new material that is soft and easy to change shapes. After that they allowed it to dry so it became strong. "Cellulose is cheap and easy to work with," says Wei. They found that the controller and the robotic arm stood up to both heavy use and a week of inactivity. Finally, they buried them both in a hole. Within eight weeks these two parts were almost completely gone.
Wei and Zhang expect that robots like these can be used to deal with dangerous waste and then disappear naturally. They also hope that such robots can aid doctors in operations and then safely break down inside the body.
However, it''s important to note that the technology is still in very early stages. "If we truly want to have a biodegradable robot," Hartmann says, "we also need to make sure its electronics and power parts are biodegradable."
 

 
